\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 General Observations}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl264\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 I think about \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Saskantinon, the Land Between Two Rivers\u8221\'94 in terms of both a game and story.  }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 This goes all the way back to playing the Gamma World scenarios that provided the underpinnings for much of it, when it became clear that the story-telling part of the game-play was what people enjoyed as much as if not more than the role-playing mechanics. Although the points made in the Story Arcs notes are keys to constructing a strong narrative, keep in mind some principles of good game design as well.  }
\par\pard\plain \tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl264\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Some interesting guides so far have been Tynan Sylvester\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93Designing Games: A Guide to Engineering Experiences\u8221\'94, O\u8217\'92Reilly, 2013 and Raph Koster\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93A Theory of Fun for Game Design, 2}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\super\cf1 nd}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  Edition\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8221\'94, O\u8217\'92Reilly, 2014.  Both books have a wealth of advice. }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 They both note that creativity and creating an emotional experience are key.  This is similar to the Udemy course I did on \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Writing for an Emotional Impact: Punch them in the gut\u8221\'94.  Both the gaming and  story-telling need to immerse the reader-player in a world they can relate to emotionally, and which, in some way, helps them to navigate their way through their own world. }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 - Keep in mind that }{\f1\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 telling}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  a reader what emotion is being experienced is really bad story-telling. }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 To this end, things that would help might be to include the same story arcs that are in the more structured story-telling, but perhaps providing options, or open-ended outcomes.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 This could also be a way of improving / finding surprises to enhance the story-telling.  }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 There should be a way to develop a software-gaming interface, or tools, that help to craft story, in much the same way that a good role-playing crew helps the game-master develop a good narrative. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The idea of an-going feedback loop between game-software-play (and development) and written-story intrigues me.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 - Use the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Saskan Eyes\u8221\'94 editor to help develop ideas, alternatives, etc.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Motivation and Fulfillment}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The very interesting Chapter 8 of Sylvester\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s book \u8220\'93Designing Games\u8221\'94 deals with this topic, providing a kind of deep dive into (and ending with a problematization of) Skinnerian psychology, showing how it helps to develop a dopamine-triggering motivational feedback loop, the ethical implications of this, and the pitfalls of trying to map simple reward-response interfaces onto complex social phenomena.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 I intend to map some of those concepts to things I\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92ve considered on the game side of \u8220\'93The Saskan Lands\u8221\'94, but a summary of Sylverster\u8217\'92s key points:}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 * }{\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Motivation and Pleasure are not the same thing.}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  Players (and readers) can be motivated in specific ways, even into very addictive repetitive behaviors. But that doesn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t always mean they are getting pleasure from it.  If the main design goal is to generate money for a game publisher, this can effectively be the same thing as promoting drug use.  At the end of the chapter Sylvester talks about a designer\u8217\'92s attempt at parody by creating a \u8220\'93click a cow\u8221\'94 game. To her dismay, people loved it and even kept \u8220\'93clicking the cow\u8221\'94 (hoping it would re-appear) after she\u8217\'92d removed all the cows from the game.  }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 My take-away there is to strive for goals that:}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 \tab * Satisfy the emotional needs of the listener/reader/player.  This means things like: providing the means to resolve conflicts, either internal or external ones.   Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s call it constructing a \u8220\'93melodic\u8221\'94 line and a \u8220\'93harmonic\u8221\'94 progression (perhaps even literally?) that resolves on the dominant tonic.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 In other words, surprises are great, but ridiculous endings (or resolutions) are just annoying and dis-satisfying. }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 \tab * Seek to embody themes that will really resonate with audience/s.  Provide characters that appeal to multiple demographics, identities, worlds, and especially to a (vaguely) \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93proletarianized\u8221\'94 class of player-reader who are looking for \u8220\'93impossible\u8221\'94 answers to real questions/problems. (See Thematic Tones:Themes)  Provide some kind of hope for a new kind of solution to \u8220\'93intractable\u8221\'94 contradictions.  Offer glimpses into philosophy that are not simply banal blandishments, don\u8217\'92t just reconfirm pre-conceived notions/ideology.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 \tab * Offer rewards in the shape of creative work, such as musical compositions, unique communities/families of characters, interesting player and non-player characters, and perhaps a degree of \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93civilization building\u8221\'94 albeit on a smaller scale and within the context of my \u8220\'93Enclosures\u8221\'94. This latter would be something like the \u8220\'93God\u8221\'94 role in games like SimCity, Cities Skylines, The Universim, Trainz,\u8230\'85 or even Minecraft I guess, but with a specific palette.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Another take on the shape of creative work is the Bogdanovian / Proletkult one. In other words, the creative work should not be stashed away in a \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93museum\u8221\'94 and produced only by \u8220\'93workers in the art industry\u8221\'94, but should be performed \u8220\'93on the street\u8221\'94 and produced by \u8220\'93the masses\u8221\'94 (So is YouTube a \u8220\'93museum\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93a street\u8221\'94? Hmmm\u8230\'85) }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 \tab * At one extreme, have a strong creative element in a multi-player interaction might appeal to introverts.  In other words, songs, villages, communities, inns, tunes, tools, meals, arguments that are created and \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93published\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93released\u8221\'94 might flow into the mix available to other players.  But they do not necessarily require direct interaction with other players. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 A kind of socially-distanced game play I guess?  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Reward is in creating and seeing adoption stats, seeing one\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s scenarios \u8220\'93performed\u8221\'94 by, one\u8217\'92s tools \u8220\'93used\u8221\'94 by others\u8230\'85}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 As far as direct rewards within the gaming model, some of the interesting points that Sylvester makes are\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 anticipation}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  of rewards, as opposed to the actual reward itself, is what creates the dopamine reaction (i.e., the motivation to play, to continue to play).  In writing, this would be something like foreshadowing or creating conflicts that call out for resolution or laying out the mystery.  This }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 in itself}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  is not enough. In itself does not }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 spark joy}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 .}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 In gaming, creating such anticipation without actual reward means people will stop playing.  Good skill and crafting not only provides rewards in a meaningful emotional context (as noted above) but provide the reward reinforcement on a }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 schedule}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  that is enjoyable and fruitful in the player-reader\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s world.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 In writing, this would be keeping a good pace of posing mystery/contradiction/conflict and resolving it, as well as continuing character development.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The }{\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 reward reinforcement schedule}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  might have a\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Fixed ratio}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 :  each such-and-such action always results in such-and-such a reward.  This simple version of this is the most banal \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93drug addict\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93click the cow\u8221\'94 kind of interface.   }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Variable ratio}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 :  the reward occurs in a randomized fashion. A bit more like gambling.  The player keeps \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93clicking the cow\u8221\'94 in anticipation of \u8220\'93hitting it\u8221\'94.  This may be a sliding scale kind of thing, where newer, less experience players are rewarded more often for a particular behavior, but older, more experienced players get that reward on an increasing random schedule.  And of course, escalating the difficulty of the tasks is a common variation too.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Fixed interval}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 .   The reward occurs only the }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 n}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 th time the behavior occurs (rather like the little \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93goodies\u8221\'94 in Waze).  These are generally poor motivators for on-going play, sparking short-term interest only.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Variable interval}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 .  The reward occurs after the behavior occurs random times.  Like playing craps.  It\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s exciting because you never know when you might \u8220\'93hit it\u8221\'94.  However, there is lower overall chance of a \u8220\'93win\u8221\'94 on any given \u8220\'93try\u8221\'94, so players may become de-motivated in the short term, less likely to  quickly repeat the behavior.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Differential reinforcement of low response rates}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 :  like fixed interval but with a throttle against trying to gain the reward too early. Encourages steady but low rate of activity.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 Differential reinforcement of high response rates}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 :  behavior must occur }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 n}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  times within a time frame to get the reward.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 There are many other possible schedules, with varying motivation responses elicited. }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 Sylvester\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s basic recommendation is to }{\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 engineer multiple superimposed reinforcement schedules}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 , giving the example of Civilization V, where there are as many as 30 different reinforcement schedules going on at any given time. (No wonder I like it so much! :-) ) }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 This is what gives that extremely successful game its \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93oh, let\u8217\'92s play just one more turn\u8221\'94 feeling.   There is always }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 something}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  that may provide a reward type of feedback on every click, but seldom always the same combination of things. Some occur quickly, regularly.  Some seldom.  Some within a certain time frame.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 It would not hurt to think of this kind of superimposed, variable-length phrasing when designing scenarios in writing too (and music for that matter).}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 ne plus ultra}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  according to Sylvester is an }{\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 emergent reinforcement schedule}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 .   This is when the reward emerges from the nature and style of game play itself.  Chess is the classic example.  }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 pace}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  of reward (taking the opponents pieces) is determined entirely by the strategy deployed by the player.  This can be a very boring approach too \hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1  a \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93death-match killer\u8221\'94 game is dominated by someone with \u8220\'93the killer joystick\u8221\'94 or whatever, who can \u8220\'93kill more cows\u8221\'94 than anyone else.  But there is little flexibility or interest other than hitting the top of the leader board.  }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1   The other interesting thing that Sylvester outlines about motivation has to do with }{\f0\fs26\b1\i0\cf1 extrinsic vs intrinsic motivations}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 .   }
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 This is where it gets interesting. Ask when providing a reward }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 de}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 motivates the player-reader.  The basic finding is that when players/participants are involved in something they perceive as a creative or social activity, offering rewards }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1\cf1 at all}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1  is demotivating. They come to associate the activity more narrowly (\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I only play the piano to satisfy the demands of my teacher\u8221\'94) rather than approaching it joyfully and experimentally (\u8220\'93Playing the piano is fun! Look what cool things I figured out to do with notes and chords based on the A minor natural scale!\u8221\'94).}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1 The \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93trick\u8221\'94 is to find the most joyful, interesting balance between extrinsic and intrinsic motivations, using a complex reinforcement schedule and, ideally, crafting an \u8220\'93instrument\u8221\'94 that encourages emergent responses.   }
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
